column169: On December 3, 2024, one (1) 55-gallond drum of printing ink was damaged and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Coastal Environmental Solutions (CES) to remediate the impacted site. CES personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the ink-impacted trailer floor. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon overpack and all impacted waste and absorbents collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon pail.

column169: ABF Checker Driver states that he was unloading trailer 573131 in dock door 5 when he saw a giant super sack of UN2211, POLYMERIC BEADS EXPANDABLE, 9, PG III had a spool puncturing the sack on side and when he tried to carefully remove the freight, the sack busted and spilled an estimated 350LB onto  the trailer floor. ABF driver states that the spool was loaded way too close at the previous facility which rubbed against it during transit and ultimately busting the sack. ABF driver states that amazingly, all 350LB of the powder has been contained on the trailer. Safety advised driver to take pi ctures and immediately close the trailer afterwards to avoid any additional spillage to occur. Safety contacted CURA and made sure that they look everywhere around the trailer to make sure none of it spilled out on to the dock or yard. ABF advised driver to send photos to Safety.

column169: On December 26, 2024, LGT notified ERTS of a spill that occurred inside of a trailer and on the dock in Garland, TX. The spill consisted of approximately half a quart of UN1824 Trupower All Purpose Dishmachine Detergent, which spilled from a box containing a 5-gallon plastic jug. The jug was damaged due to the shipper loading the box containing the jug too closely to another pallet, which punctured the container and caused it to leak out onto the trailer floor and on the dock as well. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the terminal, who turned down contractor assistance. Terminal personnel donned PPE and contained and cleaned the release. The damaged jug and impacted absorbents were placed into a 10-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Pkg shipped as Fully Regulated. Pkg has no Hazmat markings of any kind. Pkg flagged for Hazmat Acceptance Process (HAP) at pickup facility which is other than the assigned origin for the shipper and HAP was not performed forwarding the pkg to the Next Load Point where it was removed from pkg flow for proper handling.

At 0828 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal XAY. It was reported that approximately 27 gallons of Cardura E10P released from a 55-Gallon drum due to forklift puncture. The release impacted trailer # 3159845. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined that terminal personnel are capable of cleaning the release with PPE available on site. The terminal used (2) 95-gallon poly drums one for waste and the other as overpack of the punctured drum.

Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately twenty (20) ounces of material released from one (1) 3468-pound plastic tote due to a packaging failure that resulted in a release. The released material impacted the trailer floor. Dayton Freight deployed granular absorbents and gathered the spent material and containerized it into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

Upon arrival at the destination terminal, the pail was discovered leaking inside the trailer. The pails on the skid were secured using a dunnage pallet but during transit, the dunnage pallet moved slightly, allowing the pail to fall off of the skid it was sitting on. As a result, the bottom of the pail cracked causing a small release of material. The material was absorbed using absorbent material and placed into a proper receptable along with the damaged pail for proper disposal. The package specifications were not able to be safely obtained.
column170: This incident may not have occurred if the dunnage skid was secured more tightly around the pallet of pails. This incident may be used as a discussion topic during upcoming safety meetings to illustrate the importance of proper freight securement techniques.

An employee was unloading drums from a truck at Veolia's 10-day intransit facility in Kansas City. As the employee was entering the truck on the forklift, the portable dock plate unexpectedly shifted, pushing the forklift forward quicker than expected resulting in the forks of the forklift to puncture the side of a drum containing hazardous waste (waste flammable liquids - Methyl Ethyl Ketone, Benzene). Less than a gallon of the material was spilled in the trailer, fully contained, and no further releases occurred. The spilled material was cleaned up appropriately and the punctured drum was overpacked.
column170: Due to the configuration of the forklift and trailer, the employee recognizes that utilizing a pallet jack would have been a better and safer decision to move the final pallets to the trailer's end. This approach would have allowed for easier forklift access without the need to enter the trailer. As a result, the employee has been scheduled for forklift retraining, which will include a practical exam to reinforce proper techniques and hazard recognition.

column169: On December 12, 2014, one (1) 5-gallon pail of Wheel Acid was punctured and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel utilized absorbents and hand tools to remove all released product from the site. All impacted materials and the damaged pail were collected and containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal. The impacted pallet was dismantled and containerized in one (1) 85-gallon drum,

At 14:57 PM ET, UDV contacted the call center to report a spill that occurred over the road, near 5500 Lincoln St. in Denver, CO. The spill consists of approximately 75 gallons of a UN1719 corrosive liquid, trade name unknown, which spilled from 1-270 gallon plastic tote. The driver was cut off by another vehicle and had to make a sharp turn, causing the tote to suffer a large puncture across the middle. The driver stated the tote was properly secured and strapped in, and they believe the spill was due to package failure. The spill has impacted the floor of the trailer and has spilled out onto the asphalt below the trailer. The tote is no longer actively leaking. ERTS will dispatch for assistance.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 250-gallons of UN1719 product released to a 180’x20’ area of the trailer floor, asphalt, concrete and drain due to load shift. The contractors cleaned the release with absorbents, recollected, and containerized the release into drums, (2) CUYD containing floor dry impacted with product, (2) 275-gallon totes containing impacted rinsewater from the drains, (2) 55-gallon plastic drums containing transferred product only, (1) 55-gallon plastic drum contained impacted PPE, debris, poly sheeting,  floor dry, spent absorbents and straps and (1) 65-gallon metal drum containing impacted absorbents,  trash bags, and PPE and (2) 55-gallon plastic drums containing cut up totes. The waste was picked up and taken to a waste management facility.

Waste label 223160-1 was created, one 10-gallon poly drum containing the cleaned-up product and two plastic mesh bags.

At 2128 ET, Juan Franco with XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at NMF. It was reported that approximately 20 gallons of BT0222-55 Cetamine V211 released from a 55-gallon DF due to a forklift puncture. The release impacted trailer #5634362 at dock door 76 and has been moved to the yard due to the overwhelming odor. ERTS will proceed to dispatch a contractor to the site to complete cleanup activities. An ETA will be provided once it is known.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of UN2927 BT0222-55 Cetamine V211 released to a 15’x8’ area of the trailer floor and 100’x30’ and 10’x10’ area of the concrete due to forklift puncture. The contractors cleaned the release with absorbents, recollected, and containerized the release into drums, (1) 85-gallon metal drum containing overpacked damaged poly drum, spent absorbents and straps and (1) 65-gallon metal drum containing impacted absorbents, trash bags, and PPE. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: DURING THE PRE-LOAD OPERATIONS AT THE UPS UTRECHT FACILITY IN THE NETHERLANDS ONE PACKAGE FELT WARM TO THE TOUCH AND SHOWED SIGNS OF SMOKE. THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE BUILDING AND SECURED.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE FLAMES OBSERVED. DURING INNER CONTENT INSPECTION THERE IS EVIDENCE OF BURNING, MELTING, AND CHARRING OF THE INNER CONTENTS. THE INCIDENT PACKAGE WAS MARKED AND LABELLED AS UN3480, LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965 WITH A CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY AND CLASS 9 LITHIUM BATTERY LABEL. THE PACKAGE WAS PART OF A THREE PACKAGE SHIPMENT WITH AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AND HAD PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT IN HONG KONG ON 15-NOV-2024. THE PACKAGE HAD PREVIOUSLY FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT FROM HKG - SHJ - CGN BEFORE EXPERIENCING THE THERMAL EVENT IN UTRECHT, NETHERLANDS. column169: On 12/16/2024 at approximately 1630, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4992313 at the ramp facility in Welshpool, Austria, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of various clothing items.  Included in this package was a bottle of aerosol body spray and a bottle of cologne.  The shipment is discovered during the X-Ray process and the ramp.  Further confirmation revealed the contents, as an odor began to to emit from the package.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, as it was without the required marking, labeling, packaging or paperwork.  Due the international location, the shipment will be sent for disposal.

A release of an estimated 20 gallons of Sodium hypochlorite occurred during a bulk delivery at a customer site. The delivery point is located on the outside of the building. The leak was on the customer's piping system inside the building. The material was captured in containment. The release occurred within the first 15-20 seconds of the transfer. The customer stated that the leak was located where recent maintenance had been performed. There were no injuries. Our driver was overseeing the unload so we are submitting this DOT 5800 report.

When the warehouseman can in for work he went out to inspect the Wearhouse and found a poly drum on a pallet with material on the floor under the skid. He then put down some absorbent and called our emergency response. A  team was dispatched to the facility and arrived at 0900 et. There was not a crew available with the proper PPE until the next morning and they showed up at 0600et and began cleaning up the material and placing the drum into a salvage drum. the material was cleaned up with absorbent material and placed into the proper shipping container to be disposed of. The clean up was completed by 0830et.

column169: UPS AIRLINES WAS NOTIFIED ONE AIR PACKAGE ORIGINATING FROM CHINA, TRANSITING THROUGH THE USA ON UPS AIRCRAFT HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE IN GERMANY CONTAINING A TOXIC BY INHALATION LIQUID FORBIDDEN FOR TRANSPORT. THE CONSIGNEE ORDERED CHEMICAL TRIMETHYLSILYLCYANID AT UCHEM INC, SHANGHAI, CHINA.  ONCE THE PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED BY THE CONSIGNEE IN GERMANY, THEY DISCOVERED ALL DOCUMENTATION STATED NON-HAZARDOUS CHEMICAL MONOMETHYL ADIPATE HAD BEEN SHIPPED INSTEAD OF THE ORDERED TRIMETHYLSILYLCYANID CHEMICAL. THE TOXIC BY INHALATION LIQUID, FLAMMABLE WAS PACKAGED IN AN ALUMINUM BAG DESCRIBED AS MONOMETHYL ADIPATE CAS 627-91-8. THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELLED WITH ANY DANGEROUS GOODS INDICATORS. UPON OPENING THE ALUMIMUM BAG, THE CONSIGNEE NOTED THE SMELL OF CYANIDE.  THE 500 G BOTTLE INSIDE THE BAG HAD NO LABELS OR SIGNAGE INDICATING THE CONTENTS INSIDE THE BOTTLE. TESTS PERFORMED BY THE CONSIGNEE CONFIRMED TRIMETHYLSILYL CYANIDE, CAS 7677-24-9 WAS CONTAINED IN THE UNMARKED BOTTLE INSIDE THE ALUMINIM BAG DESCRIBED BY THE SHIPPER AS MONOMETHYL ADIPATE CAS 627-91-8. THE PACKAGE IS NO LONGER IN TRANSPORTATION BUT HAD PREVIOUSLY TRAVELED VIA AIRCRAFT FROM PVG TO ANC, ANC TO SDF, SDF TO CGN.
Associate did not block and/or brace freight properly for transport.  Freight was crushed causing release of product.

column169: On December 7, 2024, at 1751 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Farragut, TN regarding the release of  BPW 76910 Antifoam. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 0.5 gallons of BPW 76910 Antifoam (UN3082, 9, III) from (1) 330-gallon poly tote onto the trailer floor and asphalt parking lot. The release was reportedly due to a crack in the tote, impacting a 4’ x 6’ area on the trailer and a 1’ x 3’ area of asphalt. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. Contractors transferred the remaining product into a new 330-gallon poly tote to continue on with the client’s shipment and took the damaged tote off-site for proper disposal. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (1) 55-gallon DM, which was then taken off site by the contractor for proper disposal.

column63: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column169: While driving eastbound(speed unknown) on Highway 74 at approximately 6:00 AM on 12/16/2024, the vehicle hit a cow that was in the middle of the road. The driver reported heavy fog at the time of the collision. As a result of the collision, the vehicle left the roadway onto the eastbound shoulder of the road and burst into flames. The driver escaped the vehicle and called emergency medical services. h Upon theif arrival on the scene shortly after the accident, law enforcement closed the eastbound lane of the road. This lane of the road remained closed for several hours until being reopened following decontamination of the area in the evening on December 16. After the vehicle caught fire, the flames consumed the vehicle, 6reaching the shipping container and several of the unit dose shields and spreading some radioactive contamination in the general vicinity of the vehicle. EMS worked to extinguish the fire and in doing so, spread some contamination further around the area, reaching approximately 15-20 feet away from the vehicle. Two of the unit dose pigs were later identified in the debris, while another two items that may have been unit dose pigs were also identified. The other pigs appear to have fully melted in the fire and their materials released. It was not possible to identify which specific doses' pigs were intact. Cleanup was conducted by a contractor, Alpha-Omega Training& Compliance, Inc., with direction by Cardinal Health and a representative from the Georgia DNR Radioactive Materials Program. The area was found to be at background levels after cleanup concluded on the evening of 12/16.
column170: times, especially during low visibility and in areas with the possibility for animal crossings or heavy traffic. No current plans to revise packaging due to unusual nature of this incident. Note: vehicle was totaled. Damage costs not available at time of reporting; please reach out if estimates will be required.

column43: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column169: FEAM CVG currently operates as contract maintenance for Sun Country Airlines at the CVG airport. On 12/20/2024 Sun Country maintenance control reached out to a FEAM employee to request that a non-hazardous material aircraft part be shipped back to MSP that night as COMAT on board flight 3039 and A/C N7907A. Without the knowledge or consultation of any Sun Country employee the FEAM employee also loaded a single portable halon fire extinguisher (UN1044) which was not declared as hazmat. This undeclared hazmat COMAT was subsequently onboard A/C N7907A for flight 3039 from CVG to MSP. Upon arrival in MSP this hazmat was discovered, and the discrepancy became known. There was no package failure or release of material during this event and the undeclared hazmat package was removed from the aircraft without further incident. Actions taken after this event included reaching out to the contract maintenance provider to remind them any shipping of items as COMAT needs to be communicated too and cleared by the Sun Country materials department. An internal investigation was also launched along with the filing of an FAA hazmat cargo discrepancy report and an FAA VDRP related to the regulatory violation that occurred.
column170: Potentially additional training could help prevent recurrence of a situation like this. The internal investigation is still ongoing and root cause has not been determined at this time but it is certainly possible that the contract maintenance provider employees involved in this incident lacked appropriate hazmat training. If they were more aware of hazmat, their responsibilities, and what goes into shipping these types of goods by air they may not have made the mistake to load this item onboard a Sun Country aircraft without proper notification or process.

column169: Upon arrival to Ft. Bliss to deliver chlorine cylinders, the customer noticed liquid on the back of the truck which was not present at check in at security. Upon investigation, the driver found the 330 gallon tote of 12.5 wt% sodium hypochlorite to be Leaking. The entire contents of the tote then drained on to the ground. There was no way to stop the leak as it was determined that the bladder had a crack in it at the bottom of the IBC and could not be safely  stopped. The area was secured with no personnel exposure. Once a reportable quantity was calculated, NRC was contacted as well as TCEQ and reported the incident. An environmental company, D&H Environmental Services was contacted for remediation. The company applied sodium thiosulfate to the area and tilled the soil. Sampling was done and will be retested in a couple of weeks to ensure the treatment is sufficient. If more treatment is needed, it will be done at that time.
column170: Evaluation of using an IBC with better materials of construction will be done by the shipping company, however, the IBC used was a common IBC used in the industry.

At Veolia's ten-day intransit facility in Philadelphia, PA, an incident occurred involving a 5-gallon container of sodium hydroxide solution. While being transferred to a pallet on the loading dock, it was discovered that the container's cap had not been properly secured. Consequently, a small amount of sodium hydroxide, less than a pint, leaked onto the concrete surface of the loading dock.  Immediate action was taken to address the spill. Specialized spill cleanup material was used to solidify the leaked sodium hydroxide. Following safety protocols, both the original container and the used cleanup material were carefully overpacked into a larger 30-gallon drum for proper containment and disposal.  After the initial response, the cap on the 5-gallon container was properly tightened to prevent further leakage. As a precautionary measure, the rest of the load was thoroughly inspected to ensure all other containers were secured properly. It was determined that all other caps were secure, and this particular container had been the only one overlooked during the initial preparation.
column170: This incident highlights the importance of careful handling and regular inspections of hazardous materials to prevent similar occurrences in the future. This incident and the associated issues will be addressed in two upcoming meetings: 1. The weekly safety update meeting and 2. The Branch monthly safety conference call. During these discussions, the event will be thoroughly reviewed, and preventive measures will be explored to mitigate the risk of similar occurrences in the future. This approach ensures that all relevant team members are informed about the incident and can contribute to developing improved safety protocols and handling procedures.

column169: The shipment was discovered leaking in a ULD during sort operations. Inner contents: 1 metal can in bubble wrap (OAKITE 31) dented on the bottom chime. All remaining contents were placed in a salvage drum and held for disposition from the shipper.

On December 10, 2024, one (1) 55-gallond rum of UN1791 was punctured and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EX Environmental (EXE) to remediate the impacted site. The crew utilized neutralizing agents and absorbents to remove any spent product. The crew pump transfered the contents of the damaged 55-gallon drum into one (1) new 55-gallon drum. All impacted materials were containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal.
attachment Name:Screenshot 2024-12-21 135913.png

On December 12, 2024, at 1127 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Dickinson, TX regarding the release of Spent Hydroprocessing Catalyst. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 100 pounds of Spent Hydroprocessing Catalyst (UN3190, 4.2, II) from (1) metal tote onto soil. The release was reportedly due to the flatbed trailer rolling on its side causing one of the caps to come off the tote, impacting a 10' x 5' area of soil. Contractors also found that 0.5 gallons of motor oil and 0.25 gallons of diesel fuel spilled from the truck while it was on its side, impacting soil.  No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. A wrecker service removed the totes and up-righted the trailer. The impacted soil was scraped and collected, and the remainder of the spilled product was collected. Totes of remaining product were delivered to the consignee. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (3) 55-gallon DM, which were taken to the consignee to be disposed of.

column43: AEROSOLS, POISON, PACKING GROUP III (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column169: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, PALED AND SORTED TO THE NORTH SORT AISLE. THE SORTER NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID COMING OUT FROM THE CORNER OF THE BOX. HE LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR THEN CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET PLACED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TUB. THE RESPONDER THEN FOLLOWING THE EQUIPMENT DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST DECONTAMINATED THE EQUIPMENT. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. IT WAS THERE THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE UNDECLARED.

Local FRA Inspector Vincent Leishman discovered GBRX 711204 with a small leak and noted the BOV cap was loose. Minnesota Commercial Railway (MNNR) employees placed a tub under the bottom outlet cap to contain any leak and immediately called Rybak Company to fix the leak and clean any spill. Rybak noted they found wetness on the outside of the BOV cap and chains. The cap was found to be loose and contained approximately 1 cup of product. Upon inspection the BOV was found to have a minor leak past the internal valve seals that leaked one drip per 5 minutes time. Rybak cleaned the seals on the BOV cap and put it back on the car tool tight to seal the leak. The rail tie under the car had a small area of wetness approximately 8" by 12" without pooling. The car has been tagged home shop for repairs and an OTMA-1 was approved to move this car to the customer for offloading. The manway cover and other apparatus were inspected and found to be secure.

AT THE UPS FACILITY IN ROISSY, FRANCE, ONE AIR PACKAGE FROM CANADA TO FRANCE WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A PALLET FOR THE FINAL DELIVERY DESTINATION WHEN AN EXPLOSIVE SOUND WAS HEARD FOLLOWED BY SMOKE EMITTING FROM THE PACKAGE. THE FACILITY WAS PROMPTLY EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF HOUR. THE LOCAL FIRE BRIGADE AND AIRPORT POLICE, AIR TRANSPORT GENDARMERIE (GTA) RESPONDED TO THE EVENT.  PACKAGE INSPECTION REVEALS ONE ECO COUNTER URBAN POST (PEOPLE COUNTING SYSTEM) CONTAINING AN INSTALLED LITHIUM METAL BATTERY. THERE IS EVIDENCE OF A THERMAL LITHIUM BATTERY EVENT HAVING OCCURRED AS EVIDENT BY THE CHARRING AND BURNING MARKS ON THE DEVICE.  THE PACKAGE WAS CONFISCATED BY THE GENDARMERIE DES TRANSPORTS AERIENS (GTA) FOR ANALYSIS. ONE EMPLOYEE HAD RINGING IN THE EARS AND WAS SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION. THE EMPLOYEE WAS RELEASED AND GIVEN THREE SICK LEAVE DAYS. THE PACKAGE WAS A RETURN SERVICE PACKAGE SHIPPED FROM CANADA TO THE PRODUCT OWNER IN FRANCE.  THE OWNER OF THE UPS ACCOUNT IS 82F81F, ECO COMPTEUR, 4 RUE CHARLES BOURSEUL, LANNION FRANCE 22300. THE PACKAGE ENTERED THE NETWORK ON 18-NOV AND WAS FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT YYZ TO SDF, SDF TO PHL, AND PHL TO CDG. THE PACKAGE ARRIVED IN CDG ON 20-NOV AND WAS NOT RELEASED FROM CUSTOMS UNTIL 02-DEC. NRC REPORT WAS MADE ON 06-DEC AS REQUIRED 171.15, NRC 1418132.

Railcar CTCX 135391 was hooked up and offloading, it was coupled to 1 of 4 residue last contained rail cars which were scheduled to be switched out. In between the residue last contained and the full cars that were coupled together, there was a derail and blue flag applied to the rail track. Railroad personnel (on site conductor from Seaview) didn’t check to see if residue last contained cars were uncoupled from the full car (railroad procedure is for onsite conductor to verify that cars are uncoupled) and as such Seaview pulled the full car along with the residue last contained car. The full rail car also had a wheel chock on it. When the offloading (full) railcar was pulled, the bridge bent on rail tower and one liquid hose snapped off the pipe nipple. The railcar wheel went over top of derail and went over the wheel chock.  The derail is designed to stop cars incoming but designed to stop from opposite direction (outgoing). One liquid hose snapped at fitting and propane released into air from the railcar and hose. This triggered the LEL detectors which initiated a shutdown, and all valves were closed. The hose released until nothing was left from end of valve to tip of hose. While the rail car was still releasing an operator climbed car and turned a valve on top of rail car at 3:30 pm.      • 3: 25 pm-start of incident. • 3:30 pm-Site operator turned valve on top of railcar to stop release.  • 3:45 pm-- fire dept on site. No vapor cloud observed but did smell residual odor.  • 4:00 pm--Alex on site.  • Shortly after 4:00 pm RI Dept of Env Mgt arrived.  DEM requested report to be filed with NRC. NRC report           number 1418172. DEM contact was Jason Kasawa, 401-255-2910.  • 5:00 pm- The facility was cleared by fire dept to unhook railcar.  Site personnel unhooked rail car and                         derailed it and closed it so Seaview could move it back on track. Fire dept requested the facility                          to lock process on damaged arm.  • 5:15 pm-Fire Dept returned control to facility.   Estimated quantity: Less than 50 gallons. Estimate based on end of valve tip of hose (approx. 20 ft) 2 mins of release before valve was closed to railcar.

column169: Our vehicle was approaching a controlled intersection at 10 MPH. To our left, a vehicle (Class 5 or 6 pickup towing equipment) was turning onto the roadway. Conditions were wet and snowy, the other vehicle lost control. The other unit spun out and his trailer came around and hit our truck and tank. The other driver's trailer broke away from the pickup and lodged into the side of our tanker, thus resulting in a puncture to the middle compartment. The puncture is located about two thirds of the way down, in the middle compartment. Our driver maintained full control of his vehicle, stopped immediately, and initiated spill protocol. The road closure was to secure the accident scene and reopened upon vehicle removal. Pictures and reports are attached.

column169: On 12/17/2024 hidden dangerous goods were discovered during the shipment inspection process at the DHL Express LIC facility, located at 12-12 33rd Avenue, Long Island City, NY 11106. Transportation by road has been confirmed.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: Customer came to the back of the aircraft to alert us, that his backpack had gotten wet some how and the batteries in his computers were hissing and you could smell a burning smell. We put them in the Fire containment bag. I then went to customers seat to find out how his bag got wet and he said, he didn't know, but his whole bag was wet and everything in it. He said, he had no water in his bag at all. At that moment, the guy in seat 15D, turns around and says, that he spilled a little water under his seat, where customers bag was stowed. It wasn't little water, it was a lot of water. Anyway, two managers met the flight and took both gentlemen off the plane for questioning.  Considered this to be more of a short circuiting of laptop than a thermal runaway. Water can sizzle in electrified circuitry.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES PACKED WITH EQUIPMENT
column169: Delta's DG Management Group was notified of an e-Cig(vape pen) overheat event during flight of DL836/23Dec2024 (ATL-PHX). A passengers vape pen overheated and smoke/fire was observed. The passenger used water to mitigate the fire. A responding Flight Attendant used a fire containment bag to further provide fire protection. No injuries were reported. The flight continued to destination without further incident. The NRC and FAA were notified.
column170: The flight crew followed established emergency procedures.
